The stylet (st) (
Figs. 3
B 1 , B 2 , B 3 & C;
Fig. 4
) is formed by a proximal belt-like girdle and 18 distal spines in similar shape and size. The total length of the stylet (st) is 61 µm. With a circumference ca. 117 µm, the proximal girdle is 23 µm high, and curves into a crescent shape. The 18 distal blade-shaped spines, each 42 µm long, are hollow and fine with a ca. 1 µm thick wall. Spines are 5 µm (n= 6 ) wide tubes in the middle portion and taper rapidly at both ends.
